00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:57.520
So the concept of One
Health, it isn't new,

00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:59.460
as you just heard from Dr. Steen.

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.120
Considering the fact that
over 2,500 years ago,

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:05.680
it was actually Hippocrates who
urged physicians to consider

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:08.310
where their patients
lived, the foods they ate,

00:04:08.310 --> 00:04:10.750
the waters they drank,
their lifestyles,

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:12.610
and the seasons of the year.

00:04:12.610 --> 00:04:16.320
And then Dr. Virchow, father
of pathology, stated that,

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:18.460
"Between animal and human medicine,

00:04:18.460 --> 00:04:21.840
there are no dividing
lines nor should there be."

00:04:21.840 --> 00:04:27.130 position:56%
And then Dr. Schwab, also coined the
term "one medicine" in his textbook

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:31.870
of "Veterinary Medicine
and Human Health" in 1965.

00:04:31.870 --> 00:04:35.380 position:56%
The American Veterinary Medical
Association had a task force in 2008

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:38.350
which really started
to set the framework

00:04:38.350 --> 00:04:41.070
for how we can really start
to embrace One Health.

00:04:41.070 --> 00:04:44.270
By definition, One Health
is the collaborative effort

00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:47.220
of multiple disciplines
working locally, nationally,

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:50.220
and globally to obtain
optimal health for people,

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:53.630
animals, and the environment.

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:56.550
Why do we want to look
at One Health?

00:04:56.550 --> 00:04:59.910
Worldwide, about 75 percent of
all emerging infectious diseases

00:04:59.910 --> 00:05:03.120
in the past three decades
have originated in animals.

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:05.840
Environmental health can
affect human and animal health

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:09.590
through contamination, pollution,
and poor conditions that often lead

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:11.630
to new infectious agents.

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:14.470
And the world population
is projected to grow

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:19.920
from a current 7.4 billion
to 9 billion in 2050.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:22.430
We have to be aware of how we
provide adequate healthcare,

00:05:22.430 --> 00:05:25.060
food and water for this
growing population.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:27.380
Our health professions
and related disciplines,

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:30.060 position:56%
and institutions must work together.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:32.460
And there's always that
benefit that we experience

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:33.980
from the human/animal bond

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:37.450
to help impact the health
of people and animals.

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:42.430
Three groups that I'm going to
highlight have evolved over time.

00:05:42.430 --> 00:05:46.170
One is the One Health
Initiative, it started in 2006.

00:05:46.170 --> 00:05:49.650
And it basically is that forte
of recognizing that human health,

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:53.410
animal health, and ecosystem
health are inextricably linked.

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:56.220
And One Health does seek to promote
and prove and defend the health

00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:59.380
and well-being of all species
by enhancing cooperation

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:02.210
and collaboration between
physicians, veterinarians,

00:06:02.210 --> 00:06:05.500
and other scientific health and
environmental professionals;

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:07.510 position:56%
and promoting strength in leadership

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:09.700
and management to achieve
these goals.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:13.190
And they have the umbrella,
as we say, for One Health,

00:06:13.190 --> 00:06:15.110
of which here are a
number of examples --

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:17.100
and I'm going to touch
on a few of them today --

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:18.840
that come to mind when
you say, "Well,

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:20.710
what exactly are we talking about?"

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:23.480
And you can have anything
from zoonotic threats

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:26.630
to comparative medicine and
translational medicine to looking

00:06:26.630 --> 00:06:30.430
at the environment as
well as our public issues.

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:33.160
Another group that has
evolved, starting in 2009,

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:35.080
is the One Health Commission.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:38.040
And they really focus with
their charter to educate

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:41.070
and create networks that can
help improve our health outcomes

00:06:41.070 --> 00:06:44.280
and well-being for humans,
animals, and plants,

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:46.210
promoting an environmental
resilience

00:06:46.210 --> 00:06:49.840
through a collaborative
global One Health approach.

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:53.440
And then most recently in
2011, the One Health platform,

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:57.800
also a global group, has been
formed to try to further the forum

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.350
of stakeholders that we
have in really looking

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:03.030
at potential future
outbreaks of zoonoses,

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:05.790
emerging infectious diseases
in animals and people,

00:07:05.790 --> 00:07:07.300
and antimicrobial resistance,

00:07:07.300 --> 00:07:10.070
and the ecological
factors surrounding them.

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:13.760
Right now, this map
that was generated

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:16.100
by Dr. Monith [assumed spelling],

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:18.620
displays the potential initial
numbers that we're looking

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:22.560
at that are both arthropod-borne,
rodent-borne, as others,

00:07:22.560 --> 00:07:25.500
to give us zoonotic infections.

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:28.500
And as you well know, Zika
is certainly rolling off

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:30.080
of everybody's tongues today.

00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:34.780
It is the next one to be added
as an arthropod-borne infection.

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:36.260
Put this up because in fact,

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.780
we really do now live
in a global village.

00:07:39.780 --> 00:07:41.780
So if I look at Zika virus,

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:45.830
it absolutely exemplifies
One Health so well.

00:07:45.830 --> 00:07:50.430 position:56%
It really does need and showcase
how we bring together entomologists,

00:07:50.430 --> 00:07:53.720
physicians, veterinarians,
virologists, wildlife biologists,

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.470
environmental experts,
universities, governments,

00:07:56.470 --> 00:07:59.840
public health organizations,
world health organizations.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:03.010
Why? Because we have so much to do

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:05.400
to address this very
important issue.

00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:08.250
Zika virus infection
is often asymptomatic,

00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:11.450
and it can cause mild
illnesses such as just a fever

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:13.560
or a rash, or some joint pain.

00:08:13.560 --> 00:08:16.160
But most recently, and what
has been in the newspaper

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:19.530
and caught everybody's
attention, is the fact that now --

00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:22.140
and CDC just recently concluded --

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:26.170
Zika virus infection during
pregnancy can cause microcephaly

00:08:26.170 --> 00:08:28.900
and other severe fetal
brain defects.

00:08:28.900 --> 00:08:31.710
It's possibly also associated
with autoimmune illnesses

00:08:31.710 --> 00:08:33.430
like Guillain-Barre Syndrome.

00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:35.940
And that's under investigation
as well.

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:39.060
But as of today, there
isn't a commercial vaccine,

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:43.830
nor a specific antiviral agent
to treat Zika virus infection,

00:08:43.830 --> 00:08:47.710
so our basic research and vaccine
development needs to continue.

00:08:47.710 --> 00:08:51.980
There's also no approved yet
diagnostic test cleared by FDA

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:56.980 position:56%
to help us detect Zika virus, be it
for blood, urine, or saliva samples.

00:08:56.980 --> 00:09:02.150
And the mosquito, Ades genus, the
vector needs to be controlled.

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:04.360
And what are the ways
that we can do that?

00:09:04.360 --> 00:09:05.700
Some are looking at removal

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:09.100
of water-containing
sources: insecticide sprays.

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:11.290
And now we have the potential
for genetic engineering

00:09:11.290 --> 00:09:14.120
of these mosquitos to
suppress mosquito population.

00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:17.760 position:56%
And society has to take a look at
all of these potential technologies.

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:21.040
And then how do we enhance the
risk communication and education

00:09:21.040 --> 00:09:24.260
to help the public
avoid mosquito exposure?

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:27.160
We do need enhanced
surveillance systems collecting,

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:28.770
analyzing the data to assist

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:31.840
in whatever our public
health strategies will be.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:35.280
We also still have yet to
determine the non-human reservoirs

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:36.580
for Zika virus.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:39.430
Originally, in the Zika
forest in Africa was

00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:42.230
where a monkey had been
looked at that did have access

00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:45.480
and was detected to
having positive Zika virus.

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:47.910
But now if you come over to
South America, we don't know

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:51.840
yet for sure what the animal
potential reservoir is,

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:54.470
so this is why we need
further research.

00:09:54.470 --> 00:09:57.400
And most importantly,
because of the devastation

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.260
of what this virus can do
with newborn infants --

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:02.000
-- those that have microcephaly,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.380
they're going to need potential
medical care for their lives.

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:08.790
And that really means we have
to have infrastructure local,

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:11.800
at national levels, the
financial commitments,

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:14.770
and the government engagement in
policy development that takes place

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:18.180
in order to address this real
challenge that we're facing.

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:20.620
That's just one.

00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:22.480
There's a number of the
other mosquito-borne diseases

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:24.370
that I know you're
very familiar with.

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:28.660
If we talk about transmitting
Dengue, Chikungunya, Yellow fever,

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:33.570
Zika viruses from the Aedes
specimen of the mosquitos;

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:36.630
the one thing that we're not aware
of -- you may not be aware of --

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:41.100
is Yellow fever internationally
is actually potentially rising.

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:45.150
And the one thing that is occurring
is we don't always maintain

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:47.560
sufficient of our vaccine
stockpiles.

00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:51.880
So if Yellow fever was to take off
in an urban area right about now

00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:54.680
in certain parts of the
globe, are we really prepared

00:10:54.680 --> 00:10:56.610
to be able to address that?

00:10:56.610 --> 00:10:59.230
So those are the questions that
are surfacing on a global level

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:01.610
that we need to be aware
of as we hear and track

00:11:01.610 --> 00:11:05.070 position:56%
and see what diseases are surfacing.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:09.230
You're also familiar with West Nile
virus, equine encephalitis virus.

00:11:09.230 --> 00:11:12.410
We also have Japanese encephalitis
virus being transmitted.

00:11:12.410 --> 00:11:15.510
And of course, we have an
[inaudible] transmitting malaria.

00:11:15.510 --> 00:11:17.200
And that's a constant
struggle still;

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:19.650
we have not yet overcome malaria.

00:11:19.650 --> 00:11:22.970
And then for a lot of folks that
may have some cats and dogs,

00:11:22.970 --> 00:11:24.640
we have a mosquito transmission

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:27.800
of dirofilaria immitis,
which causes heartworm.

00:11:27.800 --> 00:11:31.620
And a quick aside, we
have a number of products

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:35.550
that you can treat your dog with,
for example, to prevent heartworm.

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:38.780
What's interesting is certain
dogs have a genetic propensity

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:44.050 position:56%
to carry mutation in a very
important protein that prevents them

00:11:44.050 --> 00:11:47.300
from metabolizing correctly
the Ivermectin type

00:11:47.300 --> 00:11:49.160
of drugs that we use.

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:52.970
And a quick analogy, if Tommy and
Mary come into a veterinary clinic

00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:55.740
with their Collie/Collie-cross
dogs and you want

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:59.510
to treat both those dogs to prevent
heartworm, there's a potential

00:11:59.510 --> 00:12:01.490
if you don't screen,
that you might end

00:12:01.490 --> 00:12:04.170
up causing the loss of Tommy's dog.

00:12:04.170 --> 00:12:05.530
Well, that'll be heartbreaking.

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:10.480
Well now, we can test, and
again, bringing back in the idea

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:12.760
of understanding from genomics,

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:14.930
the fact that we have
personalized medicine for people

00:12:14.930 --> 00:12:17.520
and we can have personalized
medicine for animals.

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:21.250
So now with screening, we can
say Tommy's dog cannot receive an

00:12:21.250 --> 00:12:24.340
Ivermectin-based product, we'll use
something else and he'll be fine,

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:26.770
and he will be protected
against heartworm.

00:12:26.770 --> 00:12:30.050
So medicine is touching
both sides right now.

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:32.700
And of course, emerging
diseases of global health

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:34.000
and agricultural concerns.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:35.300
You're certainly very aware

00:12:35.300 --> 00:12:37.850
that we've had numerous
links over the years.

00:12:37.850 --> 00:12:40.660
Certainly, H1N1 has been a crisis.

00:12:40.660 --> 00:12:43.870
Back in 2009, we had
a major outbreak.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:48.080
And we're looking at influenza
from birds, from swine,

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:50.700
and [inaudible] a potential for
them again to jump from species

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:53.370
to species and potentially
then hit humans

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:56.660
and cause some major
important issues.

00:12:56.660 --> 00:13:01.720
SARS occurred in 2003, the severe
acute respiratory syndrome,

00:13:01.720 --> 00:13:04.410
with people in direct
transmission back and forth.

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:07.590
Ebola. We had another major
outbreak, as you saw in 2014.

00:13:07.590 --> 00:13:10.140
We're still addressing
those issues right now.

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:11.620
And again, how do we intervene?

00:13:11.620 --> 00:13:12.920
How do we track?

00:13:12.920 --> 00:13:14.970
How do we respond quickly enough?

00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:17.470
MERS also surfaced, and that
again was your Middle East

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:18.780
respiratory syndrome.

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:21.370
The potential there is
even looking at camels --

00:13:21.370 --> 00:13:24.650
is there a source that can
go back as a zoonotic entity?

00:13:24.650 --> 00:13:26.850
And I mentioned West
Nile virus earlier.

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:29.700
Certainly when that hit New
York, that was an eye-opener.

00:13:29.700 --> 00:13:32.610
Again, we've had Zika, so how
do you handle these vectors

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:33.910
such as mosquitos?

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:36.120
And then we had bovine
spongiform encephalitis,

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:39.580
also called mad cow disease,
outbreak in '86 from Europe.

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:44.200
And then what have we taken for
policy steps to prevent that?

00:13:44.200 --> 00:13:47.540
And E.coli O157:H7 has
had devastating results

00:13:47.540 --> 00:13:51.450
when it first broke out when we
had the issue with the [inaudible].

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:54.190
We've come a long way, but
we're still facing these issues.

00:13:54.190 --> 00:13:56.250
They're with us and
they're challenging.

00:13:56.250 --> 00:13:57.990
So how about something local?

00:13:57.990 --> 00:13:59.290
Lyme disease.

00:13:59.290 --> 00:14:03.180
I think many of us, certainly in
the eastern coast, but it crosses

00:14:03.180 --> 00:14:07.890
so many areas, have heard and
maybe have even had Lyme disease.

00:14:07.890 --> 00:14:11.700
It's caused by a spirochete,
it's called bacteria,

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:15.190
Borrelia burgdorferi, and
it's transmitted by ticks.

00:14:15.190 --> 00:14:17.720
Well, you think about where
we live, we move into so many

00:14:17.720 --> 00:14:20.090
of the wooded areas
anymore where deer hang out.

00:14:20.090 --> 00:14:22.530
But you know what,
they're also capable then

00:14:22.530 --> 00:14:23.830
of transmitting diseases back.

00:14:23.830 --> 00:14:27.130
And the ticks that are there,
very quickly will be able to pick

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:28.750
up some of these problems.

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:34.270 position:56%
And they can touch people, they can
touch dogs, horses -- cats rarely --

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:36.580
cattle and mice are known
to be able to succumb

00:14:36.580 --> 00:14:39.880
to Lyme disease just
like you and I can.

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:43.020 position:56%
Many times, you'll just have
nothing more than flu-like symptoms,

00:14:43.020 --> 00:14:45.820
but it also forms both in
early and a chronic form.

00:14:45.820 --> 00:14:49.040 position:56%
And if any of you have had it or if
you've had friends that have had it,

00:14:49.040 --> 00:14:51.380
it's very, very, very difficult.

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:53.180
It's constantly being treated.

00:14:53.180 --> 00:14:56.090
And people are not happy
when they have Lyme disease.

00:14:56.090 --> 00:14:59.000
And it can touch all of
us: children and adults.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.970 position:56%
With dogs and horses, very similar,
you'll have shifting leg lamenesses,

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:04.960
swollen joints, lethargy,
fever, and [inaudible].

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:07.160
We do fortunately have
a vaccine for dogs.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:08.470
And people say, "Well,
what about me?

00:15:08.470 --> 00:15:10.730
Why don't you have
a vaccine for me?"

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:13.090
And this gets back again
to the research and working

00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:17.200
with our companies to say we do
have a need for a specific drug

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:18.880
or a vaccine to be developed.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:20.860
And I believe there
is still work to try

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:22.600
to get us there, but
we're not there yet.

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:25.540
So your dogs, at least
you can protect them.

00:15:25.540 --> 00:15:27.880
And when it comes to
treatment, it's an antibiotic,

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:30.040
and one that's very
typical and used in horses,

00:15:30.040 --> 00:15:31.760
dogs, or people: Doxycycline.

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:36.040
Well now, what about
white-nose syndrome in bats?

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:38.290 position:56%
Why would I want to talk about bats?

00:15:38.290 --> 00:15:42.540
Because it's an example of how
we do live in a global world.

00:15:42.540 --> 00:15:44.470
And it actually was humans

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:48.110
that brought particularly
this fungus over from Eurasia.

00:15:48.110 --> 00:15:51.440
And the bats that we have in North
America had never been exposed

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:52.740
to this before.

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:56.110
And when they did, it
really hit in 2006.

00:15:56.110 --> 00:16:00.060
This particular fungus impacts
the bats when they're hibernating,

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:02.060
and literally will
lead to their death.

00:16:02.060 --> 00:16:04.400
And we've lost a lot of bats.

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:06.320
So you may say, "Well,
they're just bats.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:08.140
Why are you bothering with that?"

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:09.440
Because they're very important.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:11.210
People often don't realize.

00:16:11.210 --> 00:16:13.070
They help with pest control.

00:16:13.070 --> 00:16:15.150
They night fly, so they'll
take a lot of insects

00:16:15.150 --> 00:16:17.700
that can often damage
agricultural crops.

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:19.840
And they're very important
in pollination,

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:21.560
from deserts to rainforests.

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:24.560
The nectar-feeding bats are really
critical in helping pollinate,

00:16:24.560 --> 00:16:26.530
and then also for seed dispersion.

00:16:26.530 --> 00:16:27.960
There, they can help scatter seeds.

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:30.110
And often times, if you've
had deforestation in a forest,

00:16:30.110 --> 00:16:32.320
they can be the ones to
help restore it again.

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:36.010
So knowing we've lost so
many, now going forward,

00:16:36.010 --> 00:16:38.820
I still think we're going to see
some significant ecosystem impacts

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:42.860
because of the loss of a very
important pollinator that we have.

00:16:42.860 --> 00:16:46.270
And once again, it's bringing
together your scientists, managers,

00:16:46.270 --> 00:16:49.770
lawmakers, and the public at large
to try to address this issue,

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:52.840
identify where we're
seeing it, and hopefully see

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:55.890
if the bats can themselves develop
immunity, which often they can

00:16:55.890 --> 00:16:57.420
and have in other countries.

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:00.200
But when you first get hit with
something, often it's decimated

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:03.070
to that particular species.

00:17:03.070 --> 00:17:06.100
And everybody also has
heard a lot about honeybees.

00:17:06.100 --> 00:17:08.000
Bee colonies -- they
continue to fall.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.880
There was a report just
this month both by the --

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:16.130
University of Maryland released the
survey and USDA released a survey.

00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:20.590
And here in the United States, the
beekeepers have lost 44 percent

00:17:20.590 --> 00:17:23.490
of their colonies just
the last year.

00:17:23.490 --> 00:17:25.930
Once again, why are we concerned?

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:27.730
They're bees and you don't
want to get stung, right?

00:17:27.730 --> 00:17:29.030
But it's more than that.

00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:32.350 position:56%
Not only do they make the honey that
you like, but they're tremendous

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:35.430
for pollinating so many crops
for the foods that we need.

00:17:35.430 --> 00:17:38.580
And I think once again, it's being
aware of this, because we need

00:17:38.580 --> 00:17:41.360
to help make a difference
identifying the problem

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:43.250
and come up with solutions.

00:17:43.250 --> 00:17:45.560
There's been a variety of
factors that people have looked

00:17:45.560 --> 00:17:48.560
at because we haven't pinned
everything down specifically

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:51.600
under what we call
colony collapse disorder

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:54.100
where typically you'll see
a loss of the worker bees.

00:17:54.100 --> 00:17:56.630
Very few are dead, but the
hives are basically empty other

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:59.660
than the queen bee and any
of the brood that remains.

00:17:59.660 --> 00:18:02.220
But if the worker bees aren't
there to bring back in and continue

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:05.270
to take care of them, then
of course you have nothing.

00:18:05.270 --> 00:18:09.270
The other aspect has
been the varroa mite.

00:18:09.270 --> 00:18:12.270
This particular mite
has been devastating.

00:18:12.270 --> 00:18:14.540
It will continue to
weaken the bee, and again,

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:18.800 position:56%
fungus and infections can come in
and further decimate the bee colony.

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:21.450
But again, they're so
important for pollination

00:18:21.450 --> 00:18:26.170
that we may not see them actually
doing everything they do every day,

00:18:26.170 --> 00:18:27.880
but we really see the
impact when all

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:29.520
of a sudden you don't have a crop.

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:31.950
And therefore, when you think
about feeding the world,

00:18:31.950 --> 00:18:35.390
it also becomes very important to
sustain and address these issues.

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:38.230
So a lot of research
is ongoing right now.

00:18:38.230 --> 00:18:40.620
And then finally, if you take
a look at monarch butterflies,

00:18:40.620 --> 00:18:43.420
once again, what do they do for us?

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:44.720
They're a sentinel.

00:18:44.720 --> 00:18:48.550
They're one more example of how
things are changing over time.

00:18:48.550 --> 00:18:52.020
And when we change the habitat,
when we use insecticides,

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:56.120
many times we can see how the
impact is to a certain species.

00:18:56.120 --> 00:18:59.730
And monarch butterflies have one
major source of food: the milkweed.

00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:01.940
Well, you think about weeds and
you say, "Let's cut the area.

00:19:01.940 --> 00:19:05.610
Let's clear up the fields,"
but you're also taking away one

00:19:05.610 --> 00:19:07.240
of their key sources of food.

00:19:07.240 --> 00:19:10.630
Also, the extreme weather changes
that we've seen have impacted.

00:19:10.630 --> 00:19:13.520
So as we can watch
sentinels, it's important

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:15.270
because it can open our
eyes, we may be able

00:19:15.270 --> 00:19:17.690
to intervene sooner
before ramifications come

00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:20.600
up on major impact to
us and other animals.

00:19:20.600 --> 00:19:23.700
I'm going to shift into the oceans.

00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:26.600
We also have a number of marine
environmental sentinels there.

00:19:26.600 --> 00:19:30.010
For those of you that love to
go down and see coral reefs

00:19:30.010 --> 00:19:32.980
and scuba dive and appreciate the
beauty as you see it all the time,

00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:36.660
or even in aquariums, you like
to look at a healthy coral reef.

00:19:36.660 --> 00:19:38.380
But as you've heard
and as you're seeing,

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:43.530 position:56%
many of these reefs are now really
succumbing to oceanic acidification.

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:45.240
And what are we as society doing?

00:19:45.240 --> 00:19:50.040
When you think about the impacts we
have from water and how we have --

00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:51.930
traveling back and forth
through the oceans with some

00:19:51.930 --> 00:19:54.110
of these huge transport vehicles --

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:56.910
sometimes you have horrible
ocean spills of oil.

00:19:56.910 --> 00:20:00.730
What is happening as we
continue around our coastal areas

00:20:00.730 --> 00:20:02.080
that can further add
to the acidification

00:20:02.080 --> 00:20:03.460
and impact these coral reefs?

00:20:03.460 --> 00:20:07.020
We're the ones that can
help make a difference.

00:20:07.020 --> 00:20:10.460 position:56%
And together, bringing in the
experts and potentially new research

00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:12.270
and scientific technologies,

00:20:12.270 --> 00:20:15.190
hopefully intervene
to turn this around.

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:18.270
One piece of news, when
I talk about environment,

00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:21.300
is even today in the newspaper,
there was a very good note

00:20:21.300 --> 00:20:24.510
that for the Chesapeake Bay
-- in fact, from last year,

00:20:24.510 --> 00:20:27.570
they've managed to reduce some of
the land runoff on agriculture,

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:30.500
and in fact, the Bay is
starting to now improve

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:33.200
as they're monitoring
different aspects.

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:34.500
And that's encouraging.

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:35.800
So where there's a
will, there's a way.

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:37.680
We can make a difference.

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:39.360
Healthy green sea turtles.

00:20:39.360 --> 00:20:43.100
They've been around for
centuries and they're beautiful.

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:45.390
But you know what,
they're also succumbing

00:20:45.390 --> 00:20:47.120
to a number of new issues.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:50.700
Fibropapillomatosis is a
very devastating disease

00:20:50.700 --> 00:20:52.250
in a green sea turtle.

00:20:52.250 --> 00:20:54.860
You and I are familiar
with the papilloma virus.

00:20:54.860 --> 00:20:57.400
Typically you'll get a
wart, but more importantly,

00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:58.700
you can get cervical cancer.

00:20:58.700 --> 00:21:02.520
So we have developed vaccines
which I think is very important.

00:21:02.520 --> 00:21:08.050 position:56%
But for the sea turtle, it's because
they're seeing so much stress now

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:11.640
because of the impact on the
environment of the coastal habitat,

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:15.040
when they develop this
particular papilloma virus,

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:18.470
it's herpes five virus,
then you'll see --

00:21:18.470 --> 00:21:20.120
as you can see in this
particular picture --

00:21:20.120 --> 00:21:22.860 position:56%
it looks like growths, and they are.

00:21:22.860 --> 00:21:25.950
But they end up obstructing
swimming, feeding, buoyancy,

00:21:25.950 --> 00:21:28.440
and sometimes they can actually
lead to the death of the animal,

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:31.160
and also blind them if
it grows over their eye.

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:34.140
So once again, it's a sentinel.

00:21:34.140 --> 00:21:36.400
And yes, we can individually
intervene and treat some

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:38.710 position:56%
of these animals, but it's awareness

00:21:38.710 --> 00:21:42.180
that as the environment is
being stressed and polluted,

00:21:42.180 --> 00:21:44.050
we're impacting so many animals.

00:21:44.050 --> 00:21:47.040
And I think it's important that we
take a look at the oceans as well

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:51.600
as what we're doing here
on the land or in the air.

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:53.130
So climate change.

00:21:53.130 --> 00:21:55.510
Everybody has a different
view on climate change.

00:21:55.510 --> 00:21:58.580
I think there's a lot of
good evidence out there

00:21:58.580 --> 00:22:01.520
that we are certainly
seeing some major changes.

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:04.030
Most recently, we've seen
an awful lot of change,

00:22:04.030 --> 00:22:07.340
certainly across the United
States, with hurricanes, tornadoes,

00:22:07.340 --> 00:22:10.510
in areas that normally we didn't,
or frequency that's increased.

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:12.250
It's absolutely amazing.

00:22:12.250 --> 00:22:13.610
Flooding has occurred.

00:22:13.610 --> 00:22:15.730
The devastation that
occurs to society

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:17.540
when we deal with major floods.

00:22:17.540 --> 00:22:20.190
Yes, we're seeing rising sea
levels because there's evidence

00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:21.740
that in fact we have
melting glaciers

00:22:21.740 --> 00:22:25.330
and ice fields impacting
polar bears, sentinels.

00:22:25.330 --> 00:22:26.630
What's happening?

00:22:26.630 --> 00:22:27.930
Who's measuring this?

00:22:27.930 --> 00:22:29.230
What's the documentation?

00:22:29.230 --> 00:22:31.300
And what, if anything,
can we do about it?

00:22:31.300 --> 00:22:33.040
And I think we need to be concerned

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:36.270
because even though sometimes you
getting overwhelmed by thinking,

00:22:36.270 --> 00:22:38.140
"What can I possibly do?"

00:22:38.140 --> 00:22:41.320 position:56%
In fact, there's a lot that together
we can do as we become aware

00:22:41.320 --> 00:22:43.010
of some of these opportunities.

00:22:43.010 --> 00:22:44.950
We've seen increases
of wildfires, too.

00:22:44.950 --> 00:22:47.660
And that's devastating not only for
the environment and the wildlife,

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:50.300
but as you've seen,
certainly like California,

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:52.530
it's touching where
people want to live.

00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:55.600
And we love the wildlife,
we want to live out there.

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:58.310
These are beautiful,
beautiful -- it's a country --

00:22:58.310 --> 00:23:00.810
and yet, there's a lot that
can happen that can turn this

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:03.060
into devastating situation.

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:05.740
And we've seen increased
dryness and drought.

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:10.470
So we as we see this, an example
with drought would be well,

00:23:10.470 --> 00:23:13.450
you need to have crops,
you need to have food.

00:23:13.450 --> 00:23:17.080
Today, more and more we're seeing
genetically engineered crops,

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:19.970
some of which now can
withstand the drought;

00:23:19.970 --> 00:23:22.330
some can withstand certain pests.

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:24.580
So are we ready to accept that?

00:23:24.580 --> 00:23:25.910
What's the science behind that?

00:23:25.910 --> 00:23:27.210
The modification behind that?

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:28.510
The policies?

00:23:28.510 --> 00:23:31.670
And more importantly, how
do we monitor all of this?

00:23:31.670 --> 00:23:35.110
So as we are moving -- sometimes
science can move much quicker

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:36.780
than what we're ready to adopt --

00:23:36.780 --> 00:23:39.310
but I think it's important that
we sit and look at that science

00:23:39.310 --> 00:23:42.260
and the policies that should
be developed to handle this.

00:23:42.260 --> 00:23:46.940
And more importantly, to do
it together in a global venue.

00:23:46.940 --> 00:23:51.220
Most recently, the White House
just released in April their report

00:23:51.220 --> 00:23:53.980
on some of the health risks
that come from climate change.

00:23:53.980 --> 00:23:58.550
And they did this because they're
focusing again on how individuals,

00:23:58.550 --> 00:24:00.260
communities, organizations,

00:24:00.260 --> 00:24:03.590
and governments can proactively
manage some of the health risks

00:24:03.590 --> 00:24:05.660
that we see with climate change.

00:24:05.660 --> 00:24:09.370
The first one that comes to mind
is absolutely air pollution and all

00:24:09.370 --> 00:24:10.930
of the allergens that we see.

00:24:10.930 --> 00:24:14.560
So how can we take technologies
and still provide and develop --

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:18.130
clean fuel, for example -- and
not have to have air pollution?

00:24:18.130 --> 00:24:19.430
Concentration in cities.

00:24:19.430 --> 00:24:21.250
You take a look at some
countries and people have masks

00:24:21.250 --> 00:24:22.550
on every day just to walk

00:24:22.550 --> 00:24:24.640
around because the
pollution can be so severe.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:27.000
So people in countries
want to evolve,

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:29.920
you want to have economic
change, but sometimes that brings

00:24:29.920 --> 00:24:32.940
with it some very big important
challenges to the health.

00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:37.260
So how do we continue
to advance the economy

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:41.610
but also minimize the
negative impact to our health?

00:24:41.610 --> 00:24:44.290
Yes, the extremes of heat
and cold come into play,

00:24:44.290 --> 00:24:48.040
and how well do we handle that, and
what does that do to your health.

00:24:48.040 --> 00:24:49.650
We just highlighted a
minute ago just some

00:24:49.650 --> 00:24:52.910
of the intense extreme events
that we've talked about.

00:24:52.910 --> 00:24:54.210
How do prepare?

00:24:54.210 --> 00:24:55.890
How do you handle some of those?

00:24:55.890 --> 00:24:57.990
That's going to be a
challenge for all of us.

00:24:57.990 --> 00:25:01.370
And yes, with this, we see increase
of some vectors that can survive

00:25:01.370 --> 00:25:03.290
in countries that they
hadn't before.

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:07.970
Or as usual, we travel, animals
travel, and microbes travel.

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:10.430
And as I showed you already,
introduction of new species

00:25:10.430 --> 00:25:11.950
that can challenge our health

00:25:11.950 --> 00:25:14.880
and animals' health,
and are we ready for it.

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:16.650
Water-related illnesses.

00:25:16.650 --> 00:25:19.570
Nothing more than mentioning Flint,
Michigan and lead in the water.

00:25:19.570 --> 00:25:21.460
We've seen the reaction of that.

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:24.400
And how do we do and
monitor the infrastructure.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:28.540
And infrastructure takes dollars,
it's old, it's breaking down.

00:25:28.540 --> 00:25:32.070
How can we intervene to make
sure we can keep things safe

00:25:32.070 --> 00:25:35.060
so people can have
access to safe water?

00:25:35.060 --> 00:25:36.890
Threats to food safety/nutrition.

00:25:36.890 --> 00:25:39.860 position:56%
Even just looking at the pollinators
I mentioned to you can minimize.

00:25:39.860 --> 00:25:42.240
Will we still have the
food supply we need?

00:25:42.240 --> 00:25:45.570
And all of this really
stresses our mental health.

00:25:45.570 --> 00:25:48.500
People have a lot of angst
when they're being stressed,

00:25:48.500 --> 00:25:50.630
and that's going to
impact your health.

